Commentary.Commentary: PITCH REPORT - Pommie Mbangwa says that it's bright and sunny, but rain is expected later in the day. Adds that cracks have opened up and there is grass on certain patches. Concludes by saying that, it is a good pitch, and expect things to happen.
We are back for South Africa's innings! Indian players stride out to the middle. Aiden Markram and Dean Elgar are the openers for South Africa. Jasprit Bumrah to start with the ball.

Now South Africa have managed to keep India in-check but they will have to bat well now. There is a little bit of variable bounce and India have a really good bowling attack. Can the hosts head into Lunch unscathed?

For South Africa, Ngidi and Rabada just came to life after having on off day on Day 1. Ngidi was the star with a six-fer and Rabada took three. They are the major reason for India’s collapse. Jansen too got a wicket, his first in Test and it was that which ended the Indian innings. Elgar will be pleased with how his bowlers got them back in this game.

Saying that though, one still feels India have the upper hand, something above 300 is usually a good score here in the first innings as batting last is not easy! The visitors though just have the one man to thank and that is Rahul. Yes, Agarwal, Rahane and Kohli did get off to starts but Rahul was the star. Barring the 4 and Bumrah who played some attractive shots towards the end, nobody even managed to score in double digits.

It has all gone wrong for India today morning! Not sure if the wicket has gotten tough, if South Africa bowled well or did India bat poorly! Whatever it maybe, India have let go of the big advantage they had at the start of the day. They would have come in with the thought of scoring close to 400 or maybe even out-bat South Africa but like we have seen before, an Indian collapse. From 278 for 3, they have been bundled out for 327.

OUT! CAUGHT! There comes the final wicket! Back of a length ball, outside off. Jasprit Bumrah looks to guide it over the slip cordon but couldn't do so. The ball goes straight into the hands of Wiaan Mulder at gully. He takes a good catch and the debutant, Marco Jansen gets his first international wicket as well. India finish with 327.
Commentary.Howout: c Wiaan Mulder b Marco Jansen

Switches to 'round the wicket, bowls it short, on middle. Jasprit Bumrah again looks to pull but this time fails.
FOUR! These are some handy runs for India! Short of a length, on leg. Jasprit Bumrah pulls it to deep square leg for a boundary.
Full and on off, driven to mid off.

Back of a length, outside off. Jasprit Bumrah leaves it alone.
On a good length, around off. Mohammed Siraj looks to guide it over the slip cordon but misses.

Good-length ball, around off, shaping away. Jasprit Bumrah makes room and looks to drive but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller and on off, Jasprit Bumrah drives it through covers. He gets a couple of runs. Kagiso Rabada has overstepped and a no ball is signalled.

DRINKS! What a morning for South Africa! They have stormed back into the game. Both Rabada and Ngidi, after a few poor overs, found their stride and bowled brilliantly. Just the one wicket left and South Africa would want to take it quickly. India will hope the last pair can add some handy runs. Mohammed Siraj is the last man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Looks like it is catching practice for South Africa. India after all the advantage on Day 1 are tumbling down. This was on a good length, outside off. Mohammed Shami looks to heave it away. He swings his bat hard but the ball kisses the outside edge. Quinton de Kock takes another simple catch. South Africa have done really well to crawl their way back into the game.
Commentary.Howout: c Quinton de Kock b Lungi Ngidi

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, on middle and leg, coming back in. Mohammed Shami tries to block but gets hit on the pads.
Good-length ball, outside off. Mohammed Shami throws his bat at it but this time fails to connect.
FOUR! Good shot! On a length, outside off. Mohammed Shami frees his arms and hits it to deep point for a boundary.
Sprays this one down the leg side, Mohammed Shami leaves it untouched.
The new batter in is Jasprit Bumrah.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Yet another wicket and Rabada continues the good work he had begun! Thakur's uncomfortable stay comes to an end. Outside off, fuller. Thakur goes for the expansive drive but his feet are glued to the crease. It goes off the outside edge and it is taken by the keeper.
Commentary.Howout: c Quinton de Kock b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Up and over! A welcome boundary! Outside off, length, this is lofted over covers for a boundary.
BEATEN! Length and on off, this lands and then moves away. Thakur looks to defend but is beaten all ends up.
Thakur does not look comfortable! Outside off, shorter. Thakur slashes but misses.
A little too straight, shapes back in. Thakur misses as he tries to flick. Gets hit on the pads.
Outside off, left alone.
On a good length, outside off. Mohammed Shami leaves it alone.
On middle, nudged to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Gets off the mark! Fuller in length, on off. Mohammed Shami leans onto it and play a glorious cover drive. The ball races away to the boundary. Valuable runs for India.
On a length, on off, nipping in. Mohammed Shami does well to block it out.
Mohammed Shami walks in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another wicket falls for India and Lungi Ngidi has a five-fer to his name. He has been the pick of the lot and deservedly gets another wicket. Pitches this one, on a length, on leg. Rishabh Pant looks to flick but gets an inside edge. The ball lobs off the pads to short leg and Rassie van der Dussen takes a simple catch there. His teammates are all over Lungi Ngidi and gets an applause from his team management as well. Lungi Ngidi is all pumped up and celebrated his five-wicket haul by flexing his muscles.
Commentary.Howout: c Rassie van der Dussen b Lungi Ngidi

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and well outside off. Rishabh Pant offers no shot to that.
BEATEN AGAIN! Just outside off, now since he is bowling wide of the crease, Thakur feels he needs to play at it. He tries to defend but is beaten again.
BEATEN! Rabada now has a spring in his step! Shorter and outside off, again, good carry. Tharkur looks to defend but is beaten.
The new batter in is Shardul Thakur.

OUT! TAKEN! Another one bites the dust and it is all falling apart now for India! Rabada has another one. This is angled into the pads, extra bounce on this one. Ashwin looks to nudge it on the leg side but it goes off the higher part of the bat and lobs towards cover. Maharaj takes an easy catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Keshav Maharaj b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Really good shot! That will make him feel good. Shorter and on the body, this is pulled and it goes through square leg for a boundary.
That went past the outside edge by a long way! Ashwin was nowhere close to playing that. He seems nervous. Fuller and outside off, shaping away. He plays it well away from his body but is beaten.
Shorter and on the body, this is pulled through square leg for one.
Well played! On middle, this one takes off after landing. Ashwin takes one hand off the handle and blocks.
A huge shout from the men behind the wicket but nothing! On the pads, Ashwin looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Going down leg.
Ravichandran Ashwin is the new batsman in.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! So the two overnight batters are gone! This is an excellent start to Day 3 for South Africa. Rahane walks off after getting off to a start. He did not pick the right ball to cut there. It was not that short and there was not a lot of width on offer. Rahane slashes, it goes off the outside edge and de Kock does the rest.
Commentary.Howout: c Quinton de Kock b Lungi Ngidi

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length and on off, kept out.
On the stumps, Rahane is solid in defense.
Down the leg side, Rahane looks to flick but misses.
On off, this is pushed to the off side.

On middle, this is worked back to the left of the bowler. Pant wants one but is sent back. Rabada has a shy at the keeper's end. He hits the stumps, it deflects away from the keeper. Pant again wants one but sent back.
Fuller this time and outside off, left alone.

FOUR! Not off the middle but Pant won't mind! Shorter and angling away. Pant looks to block it away from his body, looks to play it with soft hands, it goes off the outer half, all along the ground, between the slip cordon and down to the third man fence.
Outside off, easy leave. Yet another no ball from Rabada.
On the stumps, Pant this time plays it closer to the body and blocks.
Shorter and outside off, Pant plays it well away from his body and towards point.

A single to end! An expensive over from Ngidi! On middle, this one nips back in. Pant looks to defend, it goes off the inner half down to fine leg for one. Ngidi indicating there should have been a short leg.
On the pads, Pant works it to mid-wicket.
Pant is off the mark! Good running! On the pads, he works it through square leg. Takes the first quickly, wants the second, goes for it and completes it with ease.
Now plays it with the angle and towards mid-wicket for one.
FOUR! Uppish but in the gap! Outside off, Rahane goes after it, it goes in the air but wide of point for a boundary.
Well bowled again! Ngidi really bends his back now and lands it on middle, extra bounce. Rahane defends by taking a hand off the handle.
Rishabh Pant walks out to bat.

OUT! TAKEN! Kagiso Rabada gets the big fish, the centurion. He is absolutely delighted. Lets out a huge roar. He needed that wicket, he was off color so far but that should give him a big boost. Rahul does not add a lot to the score he finished on Day 1. A good sharp short one, maybe Rahul was not expecting it. He goes for the pull but is late on it, it goes off the glove and de Kock takes it nicely by moving to his left. A really good innings from Rahul comes to an end but can South Africa now capitalize?
Commentary.Howout: c Quinton de Kock b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: Not played at as this too is bowled outside off.
Outside off, left alone.
Yet another no ball! This time it is a big one. Maybe because of the extra effort he is putting. Shorter and on middle, Rahul ducks under it.
Extra bounce! Rabada bends his back on this one, lands on middle, takes off after landing. Rahul looks to defend but it hits the splice.
Goes back to bowling outside off, left alone.
On middle, Rahul gets behind the line and keeps it out.
Angled into middle, Rahul works it to mid on. Rabada oversteps. He was struggling with his front foot on Day 1 too.
A dot to end! On off, defended.
Back of a length and on off, Rahane strokes it to covers again.
good stuff from Ngidi! On off and on a length. Rahane plays it to covers.
Drop and run! First run for Rahul today! On off, the length is shortened. Rahul plays it towards cover and takes one. Bavuma did have a shy at the bowler's end but Rahul was well in.
On the fuller side, Rahul pushes it to mid off. Good from Ngidi, he is making the batter play a lot more. No movement for him though so far.
Ngidi goes wide of the crease and angles it into the pads, this is worked down to fine leg for one.

And again, this is well, well wide outside off, easy leave for Rahul. Really poor start from Rabada. It is a new day, Rabada should be making Rahul play but instead bowls two extremely harmless balls. Rahul will be very pleased.
Yet another harmless nut! Well outside off, left alone.
A little too straight, on middle, Rahane clips it through mid-wicket and takes one. He was probably trying to hit the pad of Rahane.
A lot better! Fuller and on off, Rahane pushes it to mid off. The line is fine here but if he could just drag the length back a little it would be perfect.

And again! Down the leg side, Rahane looks to flick but misses. South Africa really need him to be on song. The second new ball is stil lrelatively new, they actually wasted the first one and are not making great use of this one so far.
Not the best of starts from Rabada! He begins with one way down the leg side, left alone. Rabada was quite disappointing on Day 1 and has not begun well here too.
Kagiso Rabada to bowl from the other end.
India and Rahane are underway on Day 3! Angled into the pads, Rahane clips it through square leg and gets to the other end.
Well bowled and a good leave! Just outside off, in the 5th stump channel. Rahane covers his off pole and lets it be.
Yet another delivery on a length and around off, Rahane pushes it towards cover.
On the fuller side and on middle, Rahane shows the full face of the bat and plays it to mid on.
Goes wide of the crease and angles it into middle, Rahane works it to mid-wicket.
Right on the money to begin with! Ngidi goes wide of the crease and angles it on off, Rahane is solid in defense.

We are set for all the action on Day 3! It is bright and sunny at the Centurion. KL Rahul and Ajinkya Rahane walk out to the middle. South Africa players take their respective fielding positions as well. Lungi Ngidi to start with the ball.

Marco Jansen is up for a chat. He says he found a couple of days before the game that he was going to play. States he did not get proper sleep the day before. States there is bounce on this wicket and he was searching too much and he needs to be a lot more patient with his lines. Mentions that it is his debut and he wants to play a lot more. Adds they need to hit the right areas and be very consistent.

PITCH REPORT - Sunil Gavaskar says there was a bit of spongy bounce on Day 1 but the length bowled was shorter and that made it easier for the Indian batters and the lines were quite wide too. States the wicket looks a lot better than it did on Day 1 and he believes the carry will be a lot better. Pollock says it might be the best day to bat. He adds more balls might bounce steeply as the game goes ahead and the pitch will get tougher.

India would want to post a big first innings score. The foundation is laid now it is just about capitalising on it. With just the three days left now, India will want to bat only once. South Africa on the other hand, need wickets, that’s the only way, they’ll have a chance of a victory in this game. The second new ball is relatively new and the hosts’ pacers have had a lot of rest. Will we see them at their best here?

Hello and welcome to Day 3 or what is so called the ‘Moving day’ of the Test match. First things first, it is bright and sunny and it will remain that way as the forecast is really good for today. We will be having 98 overs in the day’s play to compensate for Day 2. Still a lot of time for a result in this game. So let’s now see what the two teams will be looking to do today…
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Now then, where does this game stand? Well, after winning the toss on Day 1 and their excellent performance with the bat led by Rahul, India are in a strong position. KL Rahul was well supported by the likes of Agarwal and Rahane who is still battling it out there with the opener. They would now look to press home the advantage by batting long as their aim now would be just to bat once. South Africa on the other hand, were quite below par on Day 1, except for Ngidi all the other bowlers were off color. They have had a lot of rest now and will be rearing to go on Day 3. Will we see a fightback from them or will India continue to dominate? Do join us to find out, play will start at 1000 local (0800 GMT) as usual but they will adjust through the day to accommodate the lost overs.

So, like expected, we had absolutely no play on Day 2. The forecast wasn’t great hesding into Monday and it poured all day. The good thing is, the forcast for Day 3 is quite fine and we are expecting a full day's play.
Update - 02:00 PM local time (12:00 PM GMT) - Well, we are back but just to inform that play has been CALLED OFF ON DAY 2! It was inevitable. It kept raining and the right call was taken in the end.

What a partnership that was between Clarke and Cartwright. Although Russell did not manage to score a run, Stars have got well over the 200-run mark. It was a batting master class from the two Cs. Coming to this game, will we be able to witness some batting master class from Rahul? Well, seems unlikely on Day 2.

Update - 01:10 PM local time (11:10 AM GMT) - It is raining! No, I’m not talking about the boundaries raining in Brisbane but here in Centurion, it is pouring down heavily right now and chances of any play looks bleak.

Stars on the charge! No, it is not Maxwell or Stoinis but it is Cartwright and Clarke who are putting on a superb show with the bat. Also, Russell is yet to come, 200 is surely on the cards and what a recovery that would be after losing three early on. Switch tabs to catch all the action from Melbourne Stars vs Brisbane Heat.
Update - 12.35 pm local (10.35 am GMT) Phew! Not the news we were hoping for, but well the raingods are back and so are the covers. Has been that kind of a day, isn't it?
Update - 12.25 pm local (10.25 am GMT) - Well, it has gone back to gloomy again. There is another inspection scheduled at 12.45 pm local (10.45 am GMT).
Update - 12.05 pm local (10.05 am GMT) - The rain has not only stopped but it looks a lot more brighter!  The covers are also coming off. We can surely hope for some play after Lunch.

Bored? Want to catch up with some cricket? Well, the BBL game between Hobart Hurricanes and Adelaide Strikers is proving to be a cracker. The Hurricanes need just over 9 per over in the last 10. D'Arcy Short seems to be finding his best and Ben McDermott is really playing well but not to forget, the Strikers still have two overs to go from Rashid Khan. This promises to be a cracker.

Update - 11.20 am local (9.20 am GMT) - Well, the good news did not last for long as the rain is back! It is probably going to be that kind of day. We do not expect any play this session. Lunch will be taken at 11.30 am local (9.30 am GMT). Stay tuned.

Update - 11.05 am local (9.05 am GMT) - WE HAVE GREAT NEWS! The rain has stopped and the covers are coming off! There though are still some dark clouds looming above. The inspection will be done at 11.30 am local (9.30 am GMT).
Update - 10.40 am local (8.40 am GMT) - The rain for now is playing hide and seek! It has stopped for now but the covers are firmly in place. However, it has gotten a lot brighter.
Update - 10.15 am local (8.15 am GMT) Oh, oh! Just when things were looking good, the rain gods have returned. Let's hope we get some cricketing action soon.
Update - 9.45 am local (7.45 am GMT) - The rain seems to have stopped! The supersoppers are in action but there is a lot of water on the covers. The good thing is, the drainage here is superb.

Okay, so first things first, it is RAINING! The weather forecast was not the best and for now the covers are on and it is pouring. All we can do now is keep our fingers crossed and hope for it to pass away quickly. Till then though you can catch all the action from the Ashes by switching tabs. Mitchell Starc has his tail up, that is something you would not want to miss.

South Africa pacers were below par on Day 1. Despite not being at their best, they had their moments but failed to take it. Ngidi was the only positive for them on Day 1 but it’s a new day and they would hope the others too manage to do their job.

After taking a bold decision to bat first, Mayank Agarwal set the tempo on Day 1 with his 60. Though Kohli and Pujara failed to get runs, Rahul continued on his merry way to light up a venue aptly called Centurion with his sixth overseas ton and Rahane under pressure did well playing positive cricket and steadied the ship. India are clearly in the driver's seat and will look to pile as much runs as they can get.

Hello and welcome to Day 2 of the first Test between India and South Africa. Day 1 belonged to India and they are well on the course of posting a big first innings total. South Africa have a lot of planning to do and with the second new ball just being around 10 overs old, they would look to scalp quick wickets and keep India in-reach.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

South Africa just were not at their best! They wasted the new ball by not making the batters play a lot. There were far too many freebies which India did not miss out on. Also, they weren't at their best in the field as well as there were a couple of dropped chances. Only Ngidi was decent but the rest just were off color and as a result, they are well behind the 8-ball game at the moment. They though would hope they can turn things around on Day 2 with a ball which is still relatively new. Do join us for the action at 1000 local (0800 GMT). Till then, goodbye and take care!

Except for Pujara, all the other batters who walked out to the centre got off to starts. Agarwal notched up a fluent half and he along with Rahul set the tone. Pujara departed for a golden duck but Kohli and Rahul put up yet another good stand. Kohli once again failed to covert the start he got But Rahane then gave able support to the opener. The two managed to score freely. Rahul got his ton up and the two are now amidst a 73 run stand. India would be eyeing 400 or even more. They have a real chance of batting South Africa out of the game. Can they do so?

Really don't think we need to mention who this day belongs to! India will be so, so pleased with how they have played and their hero for Day 1 is undoubtedly KL Rahul. What a knock from him and he is a major reason why his side are in a commanding position. A few pat on the backs for him from the South African players as he walks off the field, his teammates are on their feet giving him a standing ovation and he deserves every bit of it.
Flatter, full and on the pads. KL Rahul does well to negotiate the last ball of the day's play. He clears his front leg and pushes it on the leg side. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 1!

FOUR! 100 for KL Rahul! His 7th in Tests out of which 6 have been outside India! Absolutely brilliant. What a player he has turned into. Made a comeback in the team against England and since then, just has not looked back. Kept scoring runs and has done so in difficult conditions. Another quality innings from an outstanding player. Gets there in style. Once again, excellent placement and wonderful use of the wrists. This is slower and outside off, Rahul opens the face of the bat and guides it past point. The fielder at cover-point dives to his left but fails to stop it. He then runs after it and puts in a dive, does push it back in but the ball later on trickles over the ropes. OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Ngidi gets yet another one and Kohli falls 15 short of a half ton. Kohli will be gutted with himself. He had shown good patience and looked really solid so far but falls to a delivery which one can probably say is a harmless one. This is just behind a driving length and outside off, shapes away further. Kohli looks to drive by reaching out for it. It goes off the outside edge and it is pounched by Mulder at first slip. We normally see Elgar at first slip but he has opted to stay in the outfield as he wants to be closer to the bowler so that he can have a chat with him on regular basis. Is this the opening South Africa needed? Also, that seemed a plan by Ngidi. He kept bowling wide outside off to Kohli. Kohli was leaving it well but probably due to the length there, he went after it.
Commentary.Howout: c Wiaan Mulder b Lungi Ngidi

Interesting conversation between Kohli and Rahul during the 65th over. As per Kohli, Rabada was done with 6 balls but the over was still not called. He cross checked with Rahul in Hindi - 'Over nahi hua kya?' Meaning, 'isn't the over done?' To this Rahul replied, 'Ek no ball tha, late diya'. Meaning, 'There was a no ball, which was called late'. Tells you, how particular the batsmen are, in counting deliveries!

South Africa on the other hand, bowled a lot better than they did in the previous session. They made the batters play a lot more, especially Ngidi who was the pick. He got the two big wickets. However, they need to continue to keep pickings wickets or India will end up posting a big score. There is rain predicted in the final session but let us hope it stays away. Do join us at 3 pm local (1 pm GMT) for the final session.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ngidi has two-in-two! Cricket can be a cruel game sometimes. India put on a 117 opening stand and now have lost two wickets in two balls. Good-length ball, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara puts a stride forward and looks to block. The ball goes off the inside edge, gets hit on the pads and then lobs up in the air towards short leg. Keegan Petersen is present over there and takes the simplest of catches. Cheteshwar Pujara started walking straightaway. Departs for a golden duck. Lungi Ngidi is pumped up and is on a hat-trick as well.

He raises his bat and the crowd applauds it. This is his first half century overseas and he would look to get to the three-digit figure.
Marco Jansen to bowl from the other end
On a good length, in the fourth stump channel. KL Rahul lets it be.
Wide outside off, KL Rahul with an easy leave.
On a good length, on middle. Mayank Agarwal tucks it around the corner and gets to the other end. He moves onto 49 now!
Short ball, on middle. Mayank Agarwal ducks underneath.
Fuller this time, on middle. Mayank Agarwal tucks it to square leg for a couple of runs.
Good-length ball, outside off, with a little hint of away movement. Mayank Agarwal leaves it alone.
We are back for the middle session! The players stride out to the middle. KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal jog out to resume their innings as well. Kagiso Rabada to start with the ball.
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

More of the same then is what India would like, the conditions are really good to bat on now and with both the openers looking set, they would now want to capitalize. South Africa on the other hand, need to pick wickets, they need to be a lot more consistent with their lines and lengths and then be patient. Will we see them fightback now? Do join us at 12.40 pm local (10.40 am GMT) to find out.

End of a brilliant session for India! This is just what their skipper would have wanted after electing to bat. However, South Africa won't be pleased with how they have bowled, especially initially. There was good pace and there was some movement with the new ball but the opening bowlers were quite wayward. To add to that, the Indian batters were solid whenever put to the test. As the game progressed, runs scoring got easier and the two have laid the platform for a big first innings score.
A single to end the over! Floated it up, on middle. Mayank Agarwal hangs back and tucks it on the leg side. He crosses ends. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 1!
Flatter ball, on middle. Mayank Agarwal defends it out watchfully.
Full, on middle, Mayank Agarwal is solid in his defence.
Loopy ball, spinning away, outside off. Mayank Agarwal leaves it alone.
Full and firing down the leg side. Mayank Agarwal looks to sweep but misses.
Tossed up, on middle. Mayank Agarwal puts a stride forward and defends it out.
On a good length, on middle. KL Rahul defends it solidly.
On a good length, outside off. KL Rahul shoulders arms.
Length ball, on off. KL Rahul blocks it out.
On middle, defended.
Back of a length and on off, defended.
FOUR BYES! Short and down the leg side, keeps going away from the keeper after Rahul leaves it. It races down to the fine leg fence.
Well bowled! Goes full and outside off, Agarwal looks to drive but is beaten.

Fuller and this one shapes back in. Agarwal looks to drive but it goes off the inner half through square leg. Jansen runs after it, he slides but does not get hold of the ball cleanly, the fielder from fine leg though does the mopping up job. Just the two.
Keeps it wide outside off, Agarwal shoulders arms to this one.
Now follows the boundary with a single as this is pushed towards cover.
FOUR! Really well played! This is full and it tails back in. Rahul gets his front leg out of the way and works it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Outside off, on a length. Easy leave.
This time he bowls it on middle, blocked.
From wide of the crease but the line is also wide outside off, not played at.
Shorter and on off, Rahul pushes it towards cover for one.
Goes wide of the crease and angles it into the middle pole, defended.
Goes back to bowling outside off, easy leave.
This one stays low! On off, does not bounce a lot. Rahul looks to defend, it hits the toe-end.
Yet another delivery outside the off pole, Agarwal shoulders arms to it.
Drop and run! On off, Rahul plays it towards cover and gets to the other end.
Fuller and outside off, Rahul shoulders arms to this one.
On middle, kept out nicely.
Yet again, outside off, Rahul shoulders arms to this one.
Outside off, left alone.
On middle, defended.
Good line and length, outside off. Agarwal shoulders arms.
Sprays this one well down the leg side. Not played at.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Fuller in length, on off. Mayank Agarwal prods and creams it through extra cover. The mid off fielder gives it a chase but the ball wins the race.
On a length, on off. Agarwal defends it to the off side.
Fuller and outside off. Left alone.
On a good length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal taps it to point for a single.
Inside edge again! Length ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal looks to play towards covers. The ball goes off the inside edge back onto the pads.
Short of a length, on off. Mayank Agarwal dabs it to point.
On a good length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Short of a length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal lets it sail through.
FOUR LEG BYES! Short of a length, on leg. Mayank Agarwal looks to tuck but misses. The ball goes off the thigh pads behind square on the leg side for four leg byes.
Outside off, KL Rahul leaves it untouched.
On a length, on off. KL Rahul defends it out.
Ahh! Back of a length, on off. Mayank Agarwal looks to cut but gets an inside edge past the stumps. The batters take a single.
Good-length ball, coming back in, on middle. Mayank Agarwal looks to defend but misses and gets hit near the box. That jagged back in a long way.
On a good length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal lets it be.
Fuller, on off. KL Rahul pushes it towards covers and rotates the strike.
Back of a length, ouside off. Mayank Agarwal jumps and chops it to the off side.
Back of a length, on leg. KL Rahul tucks it through square leg for a run.
JAFFA! Good-length ball, angling away, on off. KL Rahul gets all squared up as he looks to defend. The ball zips past the outside edge and carries through to the keeper.
Good-length ball, around off. KL Rahul looks to defend. The ball goes off the outside edge to the third slip fielder but does not carry as it is played with soft hands.
Length ball, in the corridor of uncertainty. KL Rahul shoulders arms to that one.
On the pads, Mayank Agarwal flicks it to square leg for a run.
Back of a length, on off. Punched off the back foot to point.
Good-length ball, on middle. KL Rahul covers the line and blocks it with a dead bat.
Length, outside off. KL Rahul lets it go.
Length ball, nipping away, on off. KL Rahul defends it to point.
Good-length ball, outside off. KL Rahul stands on his toes and slaps it but straight to covers.
FOUR! Runs coming thick and fast for India! Sprays this one down the leg side, KL Rahul helps it on its way to fine leg for a boundary.
Back of a length, outside off. Left alone.
Bangs a short one, on middle. Mayank Agarwal ducks under it.

DROPPED! Finally, an opportunity but Quinton de Kock spills it out. Good-length ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal has a poke at it. The ball goes off the outside edge and flies towards the right of the keeper. Quinton de Kock dives that side but fails to pouch it. Huge opportunity missed!
FOUR! Nicely timed! Back-to-back boundaries! Short of a length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal punches it off the back foot through cover-point for another boundary.
FOUR! Nicely played! Length ball, on middle and leg. Mayank Agarwal whips it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Fuller, on off. Mayank Agarwal defends it nicely.
Good-length ball, on off. KL Rahul blocks it from the crease.
Outside off, KL Rahul watches it closely and lets it go.
Length ball, on off. KL Rahul stays solid in his defence.
Back of a length, on middle and leg. Mayank Agarwal tucks off his hips to fine leg for a single.
On a good length, on off. Mayank Agarwal covers the line and defends it off the front foot.
Good-length ball, well outside off. Mayank Agarwal leaves it alone.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
A sharp short one, on off. Rahul sways away from the line of the ball.
Lands on off, the angle would have taken it away but it shapes back in a bit. Agarwal looks to block but gets the outside edge past cover for one.
Full and on the pads. Agarwal blocks it from the crease.
Short of a length, on off. Agarwal ducks under it.

Full and angling across off. Agarwal has his feet glued to the crease while looking to drive. He misses and de Kock puts in an appeal for caught behind. It is a weak appeal and Elgar doesn't review it.
Full but quite wide outside off. Rahul plays well inside the line of the ball.
On a length, down the leg side. Rahul misses the flick.
Fuller and outside off. Rahul reaches out and plays inside the line of the ball while leaving it.
This lands on a length, just outside off and comes back in. But Rahul leaves it on length as the ball goes over the stumps.
Mulder serves a length ball, just outside off. Rahul covers the off pole and leaves this one alone.
Back of a length, around off. Pushed to covers.

Drinks! An excellent first hour for India. Both the openers look settled out there and they are complementing each other very well. The pacers bowled some testing line and lengths but weren't troubled. Can South Africa get a breakthrough before Lunch?
Left on length! This is behind a length. Comes in from outside off. Agarwal lets it be. It goes over the off pole.
On middle, kept out.
Outside off, Agarwal makes a leave.
On middle, Agarwal leans forward and keeps it out.
Well fielded! Fuller and outside off, Agarwal looks to drive, does so well, the man at point stops it nicely.
On middle, Agarwal is solid in defense.
A harmless delivery to end then! Outside off, Rahul shoulders arms to it. Not the best of starts from Mulder.
Outside off, not very full, this one comes back in a little. Rahul looks to drive but it goes off the inner half towards mid off.
Attacks the stumps this time, Rahul defends.
Outside off, Rahul does not play at it.
FOUR! Poor ball and put away! This is short and wide outside off, asking to be hit. Rahul slaps it through covers. Another boundary.
He too starts off with one well outside off, Rahul does not play at it.
Change! Wiaan Mulder is on now.
A single to end! On the pads, Rahul clips it through square leg for one.
On off, Rahul leans forward and blocks it onto the ground.
Now bowls it on the leg pole, Agarwal nudges it on the leg side and gets to the other end.
Angles it across from the off pole, Agarwal watches it closely and lets it go.
A little too straight, Rahul works it through square leg and gets to the other end.
Fuller and on off, this is pushed to mid off.
A leave to end! Outside off, just outside off actually. A lot better than what Rabada has bowled so far. Agarwal shoulders arms to this one.
Two! On off, Agarwal pushes it through covers for a couple.
Another wasteful ball, outside off, Agarwal watches it go to the keeper. Quite a lot of these today.
On off, this is pushed to covers for one.
Outside off, Rahul does not play at it.
On middle, this is played beside the wicket on the leg side, Rahul wants one but is sent back.
A dot to end! An expensive start for the debutant though. Keeps this outside off, left alone.
FOUR! And again! Bread and butter stuff for Agarwal! On the pads, he clips it through mid-wicket. No chance of stopping that. Runs now coming for the visitors.
FOUR! Agarwal loves it on the pads, on middle, this is clipped through mid-wicket. This one races away to the fence.
On off, Agarwal plays it to covers.
Better! Drags his length back and bowls it just outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Carved away! Full and outside off, Agarwal lets the ball come to him and guides it past point. Not the start the debutant would have wanted.
Here comes the first change and it is the debutant, Marco Jansen who is brought into the attack. He replaces Lungi Ngidi.
Extra bounce! Length and on off, takes off after landing. Rahul takes a hand off the handle and blocks.
Outside off, Rahul covers his off pole and leaves it alone.
And again not on the stumps, the batter need not play at those.
Outside off, Rahul shoulders arms to this one.
FOUR! Shot! First boundary for Rahul! Sheer timing! Fuller and on off, he just shows the full face of the bat and pushes it past mid off.
Slips this one down the leg side, not played at.
A leave to end as Ngidi keeps it outside off.
On the stumps, Agarwal stays back and plays it on the off side.
Back of a length and on off, Agarwal hangs back and blocks.
Three! Angled into the pads, Rahul works it through mid-wicket. Three taken.
On middle, Agarwal now looks to block, this too goes off the inside edge down to fine leg for another run.
Really well bowled! Almost gets the better of the batter. Fuller and on off, shapes back in. Rahul looks to drive it with a straight bat but it goes off the inner half down to fine leg for one.
Back of a length, shorter, Agarwal stays back and blocks.
Goes back to bowling it outside off, left alone.
A rare good delivery! Still though the line is outside off. Good length, this lands and moves away. Agarwal is beaten as he tries to block. The ball though was quite some distance away from the edge.
Outside off, Agarwal does not fiddle with it.
On the shorter side, Rahul pulls it down to fine leg and rotates strike.
Into the pads, Agarwal works it through mid-wicket for one more.
Lovely bowling but really well played again! Watching the ball till very late! Outside off, this one comes back in. Rahul plays inside the line and lets it be.
Goes wide of the crease and angles it on middle, blocked.
A single now! Angled into the pads, this is nudged on the leg side for one.
Down the leg side, left alone.
Another one outside off, left alone.
Down the leg side, Agarwal looks to flick but misses.
Another maiden by Rabada. He is yet to concede a run. Outside off, left alone.
Fuller and on middle, Rahul pushes it to mid on.

South Africa have taken a review for caught behind. Didn't seem like there was any bat on it. Let's see what the UltraEdge shows. Yup, it came off the shoulder of KL Rahul's. A poor review by South Africa. The original decision stays and South Africa burn their review.

NOT OUT! That is off the shoulder! South Africa lose a review early on. A good nasty delivery though. Short and on the body. Rahul is takek by surprise. He tries to duck out of the way but it hits something and goes to the keeper. An appeal but turned down. After a long coversation, it is reviewed. Replays show that it is nowhere near the gloves.
Well left in the end! This is on off, it shapes away late. Rahul again pulls his bat back towards him right at the end. Really looking to play the ball late is Rahul. Good stuff.
The series of leaves continues. Outside off, Rahul does not fiddle with it.
Good length and on off, Rahul blocks.
Outside off, a leave to end the over.
Two! Overcompensates! Looks to attack the stumps but bowls it on the pads, this is clipped through mid-wicket for two.
Yet again! Outside off, length. Left alone.

Another one on a length but the line is yet again outside off, Agarwal shoulders arms to this one. Not using the new ball as for now. The Indian openers will be very pleased with the lines bowled by the two opening bowlers.
Good length and on off, Agarwal defends it solidly.
FOUR! Finds the gap nicely! First boundary of the series, it comes off the bat of Mayank Agarwal! Fuller and on off, he leans forward and strokes it through covers. Races away to the fence.
Outside off to end, Rahul points the bat skywards and lets it be. A maiden but a harmless one.
Better! Needs to bowl like this a lot more! On off, length, defended nicely.
Goes outside off again, probably testing the patience of Rahul who lets it through.
Yet another nut which is not on the stumps. Easy leave.
South Africa just have not got their lines right at the moment! This is well outside off, Rahul need not play at those.
Angled into the pads, Rahul looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Well bowled but not the best way to play that! Shorter and on off, straightens after landing. Agarwal hangs his bat out away from the body. He guides it to point.
Make that 4! Ngidi is getting the ball to move away but he starts well outside off. Not played at.
Three leaves in a row now as Ngidi continues to bowl it outside off.
Yet another delivery on a length but outside off, this one moves away after landing. Left alone.
A harmless nut! Outside off, left alone.

Agarwal is off the mark! A really confident stroke. Comes into this game with runs in the previous match he played. This is fuller and on off, Agarwal puts in a stride forward and then strokes it towards mid off. Bavuma there dives to his left, gets a hand to it, takes some pace off the ball. Two taken. India are underway too.
Who will bowl from the other end then? Will it be the debutant or someone else? Lungi Ngidi it is.

That is a brilliant leave in the end! This lands on off and shapes away right at the end. Rahul initially looks to play but then seeing the movement, pulls his bat back. A lovely nut to end, a maiden by Rabada.
Better! Attacks the stumps now and on middle, Rahul is solid in defense.
And again, a delivery quite wide outside off, Rahul is not interested in playing at it. A little bit of movement for KG.
Now the away swinger, this is well outside off, Rahul shoulders arms to this one.
Now bangs it short but on the body of the batter. Rahul ducks under it. It was a little too wayward, this delivery.
Right on the money to begin with! On a length and around off, this one holds its line a little. Rahul plays it nice and late off the back foot. It goes more off the outer half to the man at gully.

Both the sides stride out to the middle for their respective national anthems. Done and dusted with the anthems and now South Africa make their way out to the centre. So do the Indian openers, KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal! Kagiso Rabada to begin. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Morne Morkel says that there is green grass and since there was rain, there could be some moisture too. Mentions that there are a few cracks as well but those are covered by the grass. Tells that it should be an interesting decision for the captains on winning the toss.

Dean Elgar, the skipper of South Africa, says that they have prepared well and are relaxed. Mentions that they are looking forward as it is going to be a brilliant Test series. Informs that they have prepared as best as they could. Says that Marco Jansen is going to debut.

Virat Kohli, the skipper of India, says that they will look to put runs on the board, playing away from home has been their strength. Adds the wicket looks nice and the wicket starts getting better from Day 2 and it is an advantage batting first. States this is a challenging tour, their success abroad started from South Africa as they won the last Test they played here and got the confidence to win overseas. Says it is going to be a good challenge and they need to be at their best. Informs they have had nice time to prepare and their preparation has been spot on. Informs they are playing with three seamers, Ashwin is also in and Thakur is the all-rounder.

South Africa (Playing XI) - Dean Elgar (C), Aiden Markram, Keegan Petersen, Rassie van der Dussen, Temba Bavuma, Quinton de Kock (WK), Wiaan Mulder, Marco Jansen (DEBUT), Keshav Maharaj, Kagiso Rabada, Lungi Ngidi.

India (Playing XI) - KL Rahul, Mayank Agarwal, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli (C), Ajinkya Rahane, Rishabh Pant (WK), Ravichandran Ashwin, Shardul Thakur, Mohammed Shami, Jasprit Bumrah, Mohammed Siraj.
TOSS - Both the captains are out in the middle. Up goes the coin and lands in the favor of India. They have elected to BAT first.
How's the weather you ask? Well, it is quite overcast but the rain has stayed away so far. The forecast is not great for later on but for now, we can expect a start on time.

South Africa on the other hand, return to play the longest format after a gap of more than 5 months. Their last Test series was against the Windies which was also Elgar’s first after being appointed as the skipper of the Proteas. They won that quite convincingly. This is Dean Elgar's first on home soil now as skipper and the task he faces is a lot tougher. He though would love to make his mark. This series should be full of excitements and twists. Stay tuned for toss and further updates.

After shocking everyone Down Under, putting a staggering performance in England and beating the Kiwis at home, India now look to do something they haven’t before. Beat South Africa in South Africa in Test series. Also, they have a real chance this time. This Indian side is a powerful one with a belief they can beat any side anywhere. Can they make history though? Still a lot of time to find that out but first, Kohli and his men would want to begin well.

Boxing Day couldn’t have been better! It was the Ashes to start things off where Australia have had yet another brilliant day led by their bowlers. Now, it is time for India and South Africa to lock horns for the first Test between the two. Welcome to the coverage.
... MATCH DAY ...
We are back! South African players stride out to the middle. KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal are the openers for India. Kagiso Rabada to start with the ball. Here we go...

Now India will look to press home the advantage. They have a few overs to go today and they would hope they can enter Day 4 without a lot of damage. South Africa will this time hope they can make better use of the new ball. An important passage of play awaits.

South Africa will be quite disappointed with how they batted. Their top order failed. De Kock, Bavuma and Mulder got off to starts but none could make it significant. Had it not been for Rabada and Jansen, they could have fallen well short of India’s total. It was a combination of both, some poor batting and some very good bowling.

Yes, Shami was the star but every bowler played his part. Thakur got two crucial wickets when a partnership was building. Siraj got the dangerous Rassie. Bumrah made quick work of the tail. He was out injured for quite sometime today and had he bowled more, things could have well been different. A collective effort from the visitors.

End of an outstanding bowling effort from the Indians, led by Shami. They have managed to get a healthy lead of 130. However, they were in a position of getting a much bigger one but the South African tail wagged. India though will still be pretty pleased.

OUT! TAKEN! Smart captaincy from Virat Kohli. There was a fielder stationed at deep backward point and the plan was to bowl short and that's exactly what Bumrah did. Bowls a short-of-a-length delivery, on middle. Keshav Maharaj makes room for himself and flashes hard. The ball goes off the outside edge to deep backward point where Rahane pouches it comfortably to end South Africa's innings. South Africa are bundled out for 197.
Commentary.Howout: c Ajinkya Rahane b Jasprit Bumrah

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! In the slot and Keshav Maharaj punishes it! A full ball, on off. Maharaj makes room and lofts this over long off for a maximum. Keshav Maharaj will be looking to get as many runs as possible from hereon.
A full ball, on off. Maharaj drives it hard towards the mid off fielder.
Shorter length delivery outside off this time. Lungi Ngidi lets it go comfortably. End of a successful over from Shami.
Lungi Ngidi is the last batter to walk in.

OUT! Edged and taken! Shami has his fifth and also picks up his 200th Test wicket as well. Points to the heavens to thank the almighty. Exceptional from the pacer. He has been relentless. Again, kept hitting it on a length and around off. Hoping for the ball to its bit. This time it does as it holds its line. Too good for a tail-ender. Rabada looks to defend but it kisses the outside edge and Pant does the rest. India just the one wicket away from bowling South Africa out. Trail still well above 100. This is what we call patient bowling! After the ball has become soft, there’s not a lot on offer. Shami though has just kept hitting the right lines and lengths, giving nothing away and waiting for the batter to make a mistake and he has been rewarded.
Commentary.Howout: c Rishabh Pant b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Another short ball on off. Rabada ducks under it again. He is setting him up nicely here.
A length ball, on off. Rabada defends it back to the bowler. Shami is always around that length.
This time a short ball from Shami on middle. Rabada ducks under it.
A length ball, on off. Rabada gets well forward and defends this to covers. Good solid batting by Rabada.
Very full, outside off. Maharaj drives it to the cover fielder. Good over from Bumrah and India will be happy to see him charging in.
A full ball, on off. Pushed off the front foot towards the off side this time.
Bumrah is bowling with good steam out there straightaway! Back of a length on middle. Maharaj looks to defend it but the ball hits him on the ribs. He looks in some pain here.
On a length, outside off. Maharaj leaves it alone this time.
Back of a length, on pads. Rabada looks to work it towards the on side but misses. The ball hits him high on the pads and a leg bye is taken square on the on side.
Back of a length, around leg. Rabada looks to work it away but gets hit on the ribs.
A goos short ball this time on middle. Keshav Maharaj sways away from the line of the ball. Good ball to end the over from Shami.
A full ball, on off. Keshav Maharaj drives it aerially towards mid off.
Back of a length, on off. Keshav Maharaj defends this solidly off the back foot.
Bumrah is seen warming up! Really good sings for India if he can bowl towards the ens of the day. He can be deadly against the tail.
FOUR! Short and outside off, Maharaj takes full toll of it as he hits it through point again. Another boundary.
FOUR! Width on offer and put away! Short and wide outside off, this is flayed through point and it races away to the fence.
Back of a length, on off. Maharaj defends this off the back foot towards the off side.
Back of a length, on middle. Kagiso Rabada hangs back and pushes it to mid on. Played it with soft hands there.
Back of a length, on off. Rabada defends it to point.

On a length, on leg. Keshav Maharaj looks to glance it but misses. He gets hit on the pads. A loud appeal from Shardul Thakur for an lbw but the umpire says no. The ball rolls to fine leg and the batters take a leg bye.
Good-length ball, on off. Maharaj pushes it towards covers.
On a good length, on off. Keshav Maharaj defends it out.
Short of a length, on middle and leg. Kagiso Rabada looks to work on the leg side. The ball goes off the leading edge and flies through the backward point region for a single.
On a length, on off. Keshav Maharaj blocks it off the back foot.
Fuller in length, right into the blockhole. Keshav Maharaj does well to squeeze it out in time.
On a good length, on off. Keshav Maharaj covers the line and blocks it out.
Length ball, on off. Kagiso Rabada taps it towards point for a single.
On a good length, on middle. Kagiso Rabada defends it out.
Short ball, outside off. Kagiso Rabada stays away from the line.
Keshav Maharaj is the next batter in.

Review! Marco Jansen has been given OUT, LBW here and he has reviewed it. The replays roll in and the Ball Tracker shows that its umpire's call on impact. So the decision stays and Marco Jansen has to walk back.

OUT! LBW! There comes the wicket India were searching for a while. And it is once again, Shardul Thakur - the man with the golden arm that gets the breakthrough. Bowls a good-length ball, on middle, angling in. Marco Jansen shuffles across and looks to block it out. He misses though and gets struck on the back pad. Shardul Thakur appeals and the umpire agrees. Marco Jansen opts for a review. UltraEdge shows no bat involved. Ball Tracking shows that wickets hitting were umpire's call. So the original decision will stay and Marco Jansen will have to walk back to the pavilion after adding some valuable runs. When Jansen had arrived at the crease and was facing Ashwin, someone had asked Pant - 'KAISA KHELTA HAI?' Meaning, 'How does he play?' Remember, Jansen has represented Mumbai in the Indian T20 League. The reply from Pant was, 'THEEKTHAAK KHELTA HAI'. Meaning, 'He plays okay'. Well, this innings has certainly been more than okay and if the weather forecast which suggests poor weather on Thursday does come true, this knock, which has consumed valuable time, could come to the fore, if the Proteas manage to save this Test.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Shardul Thakur

Commentary.Commentary: On off, Marco Jansen lunges forward and blocks it off the front foot.
On a good length outside off, Marco Jansen shoulders arms to that one.
FOUR! India now will be concerned now, considering how these two are batting. This was full and on middle, Marco Jansen flicks it through mid-wicket to get a boundary.
Back of a length, from wide of the crease, on off. Marco Jansen defends it out.
On a good length, around off. Marco Jansen watchfully blocks it confidently towards covers.
On middle, Rabada pushes it towards covers.
Tossed up, on off. Rabada blocks it out to the off side.

Well, KL Rahul is complaining that he is not able to find the ball and it looks like it has gone beneath the covers on the seats. This is going to take a while and rightly, the umpires have called for DRINKS. And Virat Kohli is happy to do a jig as the DJ sets his tone on the break.This is  brilliant from the two pacers, Rabada and Jansen. They are really putting up a fight now. Not only are they hanging in there but also scoring freely, especially the debutant. They need to continue to frustrate the Indians. The visitors on the other hand, need to continue to be patient. They have done exceedingly well so far and will want to continue the good work. Unbelievable. We are done with the break, but the ball has still not been found! It has been a good whole 5-6 minutes and ah... at last. Looks like Lungi Ngidi has got the ball in his hand. We can resume now

SIX! WOW! What a shot that was! Given some air, on middle. Kagiso Rabada stands tall and just lifts it over long off for a biggie. Clears the sightscreen with ease. The ball seems to have lost as well. The Indian fielders are searching for it now.
Shortish, on off. Rabada hangs back and taps it towards covers.
Loopy ball, around off. Kagiso Rabada is solid in his defence.
Tossed up, on middle. Kagiso Rabada blocks it out.
On a length, on middle. Marco Jansen blocks it under his eyes.

FOUR! What a gorgeous drive! The young Marco Jansen is just growing in confidence. Full again, on middle. Marco Jansen simply drives it down the ground to long on for a boundary. So pleasing to the eyes. India are letting the tail-enders to wag their tail now.
Thakur goes a little full, around off. Jansen stays solid in his defence.
On a length, on off. Jansen this time gets behind the line and blocks it out down onto the deck.
Beauty! On a good length, outside off, nipping away. Marco Jansen presses forward and looks to defend. The ball whistles past the outside edge and carries through to the keeper.
Shardul Thakur comes back on.
Oohs and aahs from behind the stumps! Just excitement from the Indian players! This was on a good length, in the fifth stump channel. Marco Jansen shoulders arms.
Ashwin fires this on pads. Worked to short mid-wicket.
Flatter and quicker on middle. Rabada defends this off the back foot. Indian players are sensing some thing here. Lot of talk going on there.
Nicely tossed up on off. Rabada defends this past silly point.
A fuller ball, on off. Rabada defends this off the front foot.
A fuller ball, on middle. Worked towards the on side.
A flatter ball on middle and leg. Rabada looks to defend it towards the on side. But ball hits his pads and loops toward silly point. Some excitement there but no damage done.
A length ball, on off. Jansen defends this solidly off the front foot.
A good short ball this time and equally well played by Rabada. A short ball on off. Rabada pulls it to fine leg for a single.
A length ball, on off. Rabada defends this off the front foot.

FOUR! Lovely stroke by Kagiso Rabada! A full ball, on off. Rabada drives it uppishly towards covers for a boundary. This is good batting from Rabada. He is not missing out on any opportunity to score runs.
On a length, on off. Rabada defends this solidly off the front foot towards the off side.
A full ball, on off. Rabada looks to drive but gets the inside half of his blade towards mid on.
Fuller on off. Rabada pushes it to cover-point this time and a single is taken.
Another nicely tossed up delivery on off. Rabada defend this off the front foot towards the off side.
Tossed up on off. Rabada defends this off the front foot comfortably.
Fuller on middle. Jansen works it to deep mid-wicket for a single this time.
Quicker and flatter on middle again. Defended towards the on side.
A flatter ball on middle. Jansen blocks it out.

FOUR! Edged but safe and it runs away for a boundary! A full ball, outside off. Marco Jansen goes for a big booming drive but the ball catches the outside edge of his blade. It flies over the slip fielders and for a boundary towards third man.
A good short ball, outside off this time. Rabada sways away from the line of the ball and the ball goes back to Pant.
On a length, outside off from 'round the wicket this time. Kagiso Rabada leaves it alone comfortably.
On a length, on pads. Rabada works it to deep square leg and gets a couple.
A full ball, on middle. Rabada defends this off the front foot.
Ohh..A leading edge but well short of mid on. A full ball, on middle. Rabada looks to work it away towards the on side but gets a leading edge towards mid on.
Quicker and shorter on middle. Jansen blocks it out.
A fuller ball on leg. Jansen sweeps it to square leg.
A fuller ball on middle. Jansen works it to short leg.
Ashwin bowls this 'round the wicket quicker on middle. Jansen defends this off the back foot.
A fuller ball, on off. Rabada drives it to long off for a single this time.
Nicely tossed up on middle. Rabada gets forward and defends it.
A dot to end! On off, Jansen lunges and keeps it out.
Another one on the fuller side, Jansen plays it to mid off.
Beaten! Shami hits the perfect length, outside off, nipping away. Jansen looks to drive but is beaten. The ball was whiskers away from getting the outside edge.
FOUR! Edgy again! Fuller and on off, Jansen looks to drive but does so inside the line. It is more off the outside edge but past point and into the fence.
On off, defended.
Fuller and on middle, kept out.
Tossed up on middle, it is kept out.
On the stumps, blocked.
Gives it air but bowls it a little too full, this is eased down to long on for one.
Flatter this time and on off, Jansen hangs back and blocks.
Close! On middle, Jansen looks to flick, it goes uppishly but falls short of the short leg fielder who dives to his left.
Tossed up on off, defended.

EDGY FOUR! South Africa won't mind how they come as long as they do. Vital runs these. Fuller and on middle, this one shapes away. Rabada looks to play it with a straight bat. This goes off the outer half past point and into the fence.
On off, blocked.
Kagiso Rabada is the new batter in.

OUT! Edged and taken! The indecisiveness costs Bavuma. Shami has another one. What a spell this is from him. The last recognised batter is out of here for the hosts. This is a length ball outside off. Bavuma is not sure whether this will tail back in or no. He looks to defend. This one goes straight on. He realises he could leave it and tries to do so half heatedly. Too late as the ball kisses the outside edge and Pant does the rest.
Commentary.Howout: c Rishabh Pant b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Good-length ball, on off. Temba Bavuma looks to defend. The ball goes off the outside edge to backward point.

FOUR! FIFTY! This was short and on middle, Temba Bavuma swivels and pulls it to deep square leg for a boundary. He raises his bat and soaks applause from the dressing room. Has been a gritty knock from him and would look to convert it to a bigger one.
A full ball, on off. Bavuma pushes it to mid on this time.
A shorter length delivery on off. Jansen goes back and defends it.
Quicker and shorter on off. Jansen defends this off the back foot towards the off side.
A fuller ball, on off. Jansen pushes it back to the bowler.
Quicker on middle. Defended towards the on side.
Fuller on off. Defended off the front foot.
A flatter ball, on off. Jansen defends this off the back foot.
A full ball, on off. Bavuma defends this off the front foot towards covers.
On a length, around off. Bavuma defends this off the back foot.
A full ball, on middle. Jansen works it to mid-wicket and gets a single.
A short ball, outside off. Jansen leaves it alone this time.
On a length, on middle. Jansen works it to deep square leg and gets a couple.
Back of a length, outside off. Jansen lets it go comfortably.
Tossed up on off. Jansen defends this off the front foot. The ball hits the inside half of his blade and goes behind square on the on side. A single taken.
A fuller ball, on off. Driven to long on this time.
Fuller on middle. Pushed towards mid-wicket.
Quicker and flatter on middle. Bavuma works it behind square on the on side.
A tossed up delivery on off. Jansen pushes this off the front foot square on the off side for a single.
A fuller delivery on middle. Bavuma works it to mid-wicket for a single.
The debutant, Marco Jansen walks out to bat now.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Shami strikes! A fuller delivery outside off. Mulder goes for a big booming drive but the ball catches the outside edge of his blade. It goes back to Pant behind the stumps and he takes an easy catch.South Africa lose their sixth wicket. Mohammed Shami has the knack of breaking partnerships when needed and he has done that once again. Mulder held his ground there, he wasn’t ready to go, waited for the umpire to raise his finger which he eventually did and then walked off. Also, the umpire did not raise his finger because don't think anyone appealed. The Indians just celebrated. The umpire will give his verdict only if someone asks, right? Guess someone did appeal later and that is why, the umpire raised his finger and eventually, Mulder walked off. There was also a slight eye contact between the two umpires on the legality of the catch but the square leg umpire was sure that Pant had taken it cleanly.
Commentary.Howout: c Rishabh Pant b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length, outside off. Mulder shoulders his arms to this one. Good carry and bounce for Shami.
Back of a length, on middle. Bavuma nudges it to mid-wicket for a single.
Good ball. On a length and nipping in a little. Mulder gets the inside half of his blade towards fine leg for a single.

On the pads this time. Mulder works it to fine leg for a single.

On a length, outside off. Mulder leaves it alone.

FOUR! This time a streaky boundary! Back of a length, around off. Bavuma gets on the back foot and opens the face of his blade a little and gets it through gap towards third man for a boundary.
FOUR! Another beautiful shot from Bavuma! A full delivery on middle. Bavuma drives it straight back past the bowler for another boundary.
On a length, on off. Defended off the front foot.
FOUR! Short ball and punished this time! Short and wide outside off. Bavuma  hangs back and punches this off the back foot through cover-point for a boundary.
FOUR! First boundary of the final session! An overpitched delivery on off. Mulder gets forward and drives it crisply through covers for a boundary.
A length ball, on off. Mulder gets forward and blocks it.
A good-length delivery and seaming away a little this time. Mulder defends this with soft hands towards point.
Ohh...A good ball again. On a length and nipping in with a low bounce. Muder defends this off the front foot towards the on side.
On a length and nipping in a little. Mulder defends it towards the on side.
On a length, on off. Mulder is right behind it to block it.

Mohammed Siraj to bowl from the opposite end.
NO BALL! A length ball, on off. Bavuma defends this off the front foot towards the off side.

Good-length delivery again, outside off. Seaming away. Bavuma leaves it alone again.
On a good-length, around off. Bavuma leaves it alone. Good bounce there for Thakur.

We are back for the final session! Indian players stride out to the middle. Temba Bavuma and Wiaan Mulder jog out as well.  Shardul Thakur will start with the ball.
... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

For South Africa, they need one more good stand and need one of Bavuma or Mulder to score big. Not a lot of batting left after this pair and the trail is still 218. South Africa will not want to be conceding a big lead. Can they bounce back in the last session? Do join us at 7.00 pm IST (1.30 pm GMT) to find out.

An excellent session for India and they are well and truly ahead in the game! 4 wickets is what they have taken in this session. Also, they did this without Bumrah who went in injured early in the session. Shami was the star as he got two. Siraj also bowled well and was rewarded with the big wicket of Rassie. There was a partnership then building between de Kock and Bavuma but Thakur played his part and broke the stand. India now know a wicket more and they will be into the bowlers. More of the same is what they will want after the break.
A maiden to end the over! Another short ball, on middle. Wiaan Mulder again sits under it. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 3!
Short, on middle. Wiaan Mulder sits under it.
On middle and leg. Wiaan Mulder prods and looks to tuck but gets struck on the pads.

Length, outside off. Wiaan Mulder shoulders arms.
Close! On a good length, around off, shaping away. Temba Bavuma looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.

Fuller and outside off, Mulder shoulders arms to this one.

Wiaan Mulder is the next batter in.

OUT! DRAGS IT ON! Thakur, who has the knack of picking wickets has done it for India! Gets the big wicket of de Kock. Vital breakthrough as this partnership was looking good. Poor shot form de Kock and he knows it. He just ended up doing nothing there. It is a harmless ball outside off. De Kock hangs his bat out, half-heartedly. It takes the inside edge and then crashes onto the stumps. Half the side back in the hut for South Africa. They still trail by another 223.
Commentary.Howout: b Shardul Thakur

Commentary.Commentary: Shardul Thakur is back into the attack. Good news for India as Jasprit Bumrah is back on the field.
Outside off, an easy leave.

Bavuma looks to defend but misses. It hits the pad and Siraj appeals. It is a loud, loud appeal but turned down. India review but replays show that it is going down leg. Kohli is not happy with the Hawk Eye, he can't believe that is going down leg.
Angled into the pads, de Kock works it through square leg and gets to the other end.

On a good length, outside off. Quinton de Kock shoulders arms.

DRINKS! South Africa are in big, big trouble! They have lost 4 and still trail by another 266 runs. A lot will rely on the two batting out there. They have started well but need to continue. There is still a long way to go. India on the other hand will want to continue what they have been doing so far. The visitors will know that they are just couple of wickets away from entering the tail. Will the away side continue to dominate? Time for some spin now! Ravichandran Ashwin comes on.

On middle, blocked.
Fuller and on middle, Rassie works it to mid-wicket.
Good length and on off, Bavuma looks to push, it goes off the inner half to mid-wicket.
The new batter in is Temba Bavuma.

OUT! TIMBER! Markram has to walk back courtesy a beauty from Shami. Almost unplayable. This lands on middle and then moves away. Markram is squared up as he tries to block. He does nothing wrong but try to play the original trajectory of the ball. The ball moves enough to beat the outside edge and hit the off pole.
Commentary.Howout: b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Three leaves in a row! Outside off again, Markram shoulders arms to this one.
Yet another delivery outside off, easy leave.
Outside off, left alone.
Beaten! Snorter. Shorter and outside off, Markram looks to push at it, there is extra bounce. He is beaten.
Half an appeal but turned down. Outside off, tails back in a little. Rassie leaves it alone. It hits the flap of the pad and goes to the keeper.

Jasprit Bumrah is down on the pitch in pain. He twisted his ankle on the followthrough. The physios are attending him but he is still in pain. He is walking off the field now. Mohammed Siraj will complete his over.
Well, well, well, the replay shows that there wasn't an inside edge at all on 9.2. It went off the thigh pad of Aiden Markram's instead. So, wouldn't count as a drop catch.
Yet another back of a length ball and on off, this is pushed to covers. Bumrah is down on the ground. He is in a lot of pain.
And again, this one takes off from outside off, Rassie leaves it alone.
Shorter in length and angling into middle, this is worked on the leg side.
Easy leave again as this is not bowled on the stumps.
Bumrah goes wide of the crease but bowls it outside off, not played at.
On middle, defended.
Another leave as this is also bowled outside off.
Outside off, left alone.
On off, defended.

Put down! That could be a big drop! This lands on middle, it moves away. Markram is squared up as he tries to block. The ball goes off the outside edge and in between slip and the keeper. Pant dives, it hits the glove, more of the top of the fingers and then hits the first slip fielder who dives to his left. This could prove costly. Markram is probably South Africa's best batter at the moment.
Length and not in line of the stumps, left alone.
Angling in on the stumps, Rassie plays it back to the bowler.
On off, Rassie stays back and plays it to covers.
Yet another delivery outside off, left alone again.
Very well bowled! Length and just outside off, this one lands and then moves away. Rassie looks to defend but is beaten.
Outside off and on a length. Left alone.
That has taken off! Might have hurt Rassie. Length and on off, this one gets big on the batter. Rassie looks to defend by taking a hand off the handle. He gets hit on the glove.
Jasprit Bumrah to bowl from the other end.
A dot to end a successful over. Outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Lovely timing! Angled into the pads, this is clipped through mid-wicket. This one races away to the fence.
Rassie is underway! On off, this is pushed towards cover for one.
Rassie van der Dussen walks out to bat at No.4.

OUT! TIMBER! Shami strikes and India are rewarded immediately after the break. Excellent delivery. Length and outside off. This one jags back in. Keegan goes searching for the ball. He prods forward and tries to play it ahead of his body. The ball sneaks through the gap between bat and pad and hits the stumps. South Africa in trouble now. Replays actually showed there was an inside edge onto the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length and on off, Keegan stands tall and defends.
FOUR! Runs straightaway! Slightly shorter in length and outside off, Keegan does well, he rides on top of the bounce and with soft hands, guides it past point for a boundary.
We are back fot the middle session! Indian players stride out to the middle. Aiden Markram and Keegan Petersen walk out to resume their innings as well. Mohammed Shami to start with the ball.
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

South Africa will hope they two can cash in on conditions which seem good to bat. They need a good stand between the two and lay a foundation. India on the other hand, will need to be patient, there isn’t a lot on offer from the wicket so they need to stick to the right lines and lengths and be patient. An important session awaits after the break. Do join us at 12.40 pm local (10.40 am GMT) for that.

Really not sure who will be pleased heading into the break! Would have said South Africa had they not lose Elgar but now, India won’t be disappointed after the collapse earlier on. They would have wanted to start off well with the ball and have done so. However, Markram and Petersen have looked quite assured after the loss of the wicket.
Back of a length, outside off. Keegan Petersen hops and taps it to backward point for a single. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3!
Good-length ball, outside off. Left alone.

FOUR! Great punch! A little fuller, on off. Keegan Petersen gets on the front foot and punches it through covers. No stopping that one and the ball races away to the boundary. Such a good-looking shot that!
Right on the money! On a good length, on off. Keegan Petersen does well to get behind the line and defend it out. He is looking really solid.
Good-length ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen shoulders arms.
Back of a length, outside off. Keegan Petersen stands up on his toes and pokes it to point.
On a length, on middle and leg, angling in. Aiden Markram looks to defend but gets hit on the pads.
On middle, this is nudged to mid-wicket. Rishabh Pant behind the stumps yells that, make Aiden Markram play deliveries as much as possible.
Good-length ball, on off. Aiden Markram watches it closely and defends it from the crease.
This time, it is on the pads. Keegan Petersen works it behind square on the leg side for a single.
On a good length again, on middle. Keegan Petersen defends it with a straight bat.
Starts with a good-length ball, on off. Keegan Petersen covers the line and defends it back to the bowler.
Bangs a bouncer, on middle. Aiden Markram sits under it.
On a good length, in the fifth stump channel. Aiden Markram with an easy leave.
Good-length ball, on middle. Aiden Markram pushes it to mid on.
On a length, on off. Keegan Petersen looks to defend. The ball goes off the inner half to square leg. He crosses ends.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping back in. Keegan Petersen shoulders arms.
On a good length, on middle. Keegan Petersen tucks it on the leg side.
A dot to end! On middle, it is pushed to mid on.
Fuller and on middle, Markram drives but to mid on.
Solid! On off, kept out nicely.
Fuller and on off, Markram looks to drive but it goes off the inner half to mid on.
FOUR! Put away in style! Full and outside off, Markram opens the face of the bat and carves it through point for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone nicely.
FOUR! Gets off the mark with a boundary! Length ball, on middle. Keegan Petersen gets across and flicks it past square leg. The ball races away to the boundary. Good shot to get off the mark.
Good-length ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen offers no shot to that one.
Fuller and on off. Keegan Petersen defends it back to the bowler.
On a good length, on off, nipping in. Keegan Petersen covers the line and taps it to point.
Good-length ball, in the corridor of uncertainty. Keegan Petersen watches the ball closely and makes a leave.
A little fuller, outside off, swings back in a little late. Keegan Petersen shoulders arms.

Good-length ball, on middle and leg, angling in. Aiden Markram looks to defend but misses. He gets rapped on the pads. A loud appeal follows from Mohammed Siraj and Co. but the umpire is unmoved. Probably going down leg.
On a length, outside off. Aiden Markram leaves it alone.
Angles this one down the leg side. Aiden Markram looks to flick but misses.
Good-length ball, on top of off. Aiden Markram defends it to cover-point.
FOUR! Good shot! This was on a length, angling on the pads. Aiden Markram clips it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
On a good length, outside off. Aiden Markram defends it to the off side.
Mohammed Siraj to bowl from the other end.
Good-length ball, on middle. Keegan Petersen pushes it back to the bowler.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! There's the first early wicket. Just the start India would have hoped for. Jasprit Bumrah is all pumped up and he is off celebrating. Gets the breakthrough for his team and it is, the South African skipper, Dean Elgar who departs for a timid score. This was on on length, on off, moving away. Dean Elgar is stuck at his crease. He had to play the shot but the ball goes off the outside edge and carries through to the keeper. Rishabh Pant makes no mistake behind. He flies to his left and takes a brillaint catch tumbling over. Keegan Petersen walks out to bat at No.3
Commentary.Howout: c Rishabh Pant b Jasprit Bumrah

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, on off. Aiden Markram hops and taps it to the off side for a quick single.
And again! Good-length ball, on off, coming back in. Aiden Markram looks to work it on the off side. He gets struck on the pads.
That jagged back in a long way! Good-length ball, coming back in sharply, on middle. Aiden Markram leaves it alone. The ball goes just over the stumps.
Bumrah starts with a good-length ball, on middle. Dean Elgar tips the ball to the off side for a single and gets off the mark.

Mike Haysman is down for the Pitch Report,  he says he checked a few websites and all say there is a chance of rain around 1 and 3. States some the cracks are getting wider. Mentions Bumrah operates at around 7 meters from the stumps and there are cracks there and it is not going to be an easy day for the batters.

Kl Rahul is down for the chat, he says he wanted to be disciplined and he realised he needed to be patient on this wicket and capitalise on the new ball and he just wanted to stay out there and enjoy. Adds they have worked hard in the last 3 days and they now have a great chance to win and they just need to hit the right areas and be disciplined. States they just need to be disciplined and the bowlers have always adjusted to the pitches and they will try to do the same today too.

There is a slight halt in play! India are not happy with the ball they have been given. Ashwin feels this is not the ball they picked. The ball is now being changed. The box of balls come out. The ball has been selected and we are ready to begin! Aiden Markram and Dean Elgar will open the innings for South Africa and Jasprit Bumrah will begin the proceedings with the new ball. Here we go...

Now it is time for their batters to focus. A mammoth task awaits ahead. There are more than 50 overs left on Day 4. Their first aim though will be to enter Tea unscathed. India on the other hand will love a wicket at least before the break. Stay tuned.

For South Africa, Jansen was the star with the ball. He ended with a four-fer. Rabada too ended up with 4 and Ngidi got two. They bowled really well in the first session but in the second, there were far too many boundary deliveries. Maybe in the search of wickets but had they managed to control the run-flow as well, they could have been in a stronger position.

It all started with Jansen getting Kohli, the Indian batters though played with a very aggressive approach in this session. Rahane, Pant and Ashwin, all came out and managed to score quickly. All three of them got to starts but none could go on to make a big score. The main focus of India was probably to get the runs quickly and they have surely done that.
